# Operating Optikk with the optikk CLI

Optikk is an OpenTelemetry-native observability platform (https://optikk.in).
This guide teaches an AI coding agent to drive the full lifecycle through the
`optikk` CLI: account signup, team onboarding, instrumentation, and
investigating production issues.

If `optikk` is not installed yet:

    curl -fsSL https://optikk.in/install.sh | sh

## Rules

- Always pass `--agent` (or set `OPTIKK_AGENT=1`). stdout is then data — one
  JSON document per command. Failures print one JSON envelope on stderr:
  `{"error":"…","code":"auth","api_code":"UNAUTHORIZED","exit_code":3,"hint":"…"}`.
- Never parse table output or human prose; branch on exit codes and JSON.
- Exit codes: {{.ExitCodesLine}}
- Destructive commands (`dashboards delete`, `monitors delete`, `keys revoke`,
  `update`) always require `--yes`; agent mode never auto-confirms.
- The full machine-readable command tree: `optikk agent schema`.

## Authentication

- Headless: `optikk auth login --email … --password …`, or set `OPTIKK_TOKEN`.
- Human present: `optikk login --agent` emits
  `{"status":"approval_pending","verification_url":…,"user_code":…}` — relay
  the URL and code to the user, then the command blocks until they approve.
- Check the session anytime: `optikk whoami --agent`.

## Onboarding (signup → instrument → verify)

1. Signup requires the user's explicit consent to the Terms of Service
   (https://optikk.in/terms) and Privacy Policy. Never pass `--accept-terms`
   on your own — ask the user first and only proceed once they agree.
2. `optikk onboard --agent --email … --password … --name … --org … --accept-terms`
   returns `api_key` and `otlp` (`endpoint` + `headers`).
3. Configure the service's OpenTelemetry exporter with that pair:
   `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` and `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_HEADERS`.
4. Generate traffic, then loop `optikk verify --agent --from 15m` until it
   exits 0 — the JSON report shows per-signal record counts.

